This page is a supplementary teaching scaffold for semantic environments and type identity.

## Core concept

A semantic environment maps source names and parsed type shapes to identities the compiler can compare reliably.

## Beanstalk boundary

Each compiled module owns one local `TypeEnvironment`.

- Local `TypeId` equality is valid only inside that environment.
- Cross-module interfaces use stable canonical type identities.
- A consumer may intern local handles for imported canonical types.
- `DataType` is syntax or diagnostic shape after semantic resolution.
- Access modes remain separate from type identity.
- Public interfaces cannot expose private or unavailable identities.

AST consumes bound visibility rather than rebuilding imports.

## Rewrite focus

Explain nominal identity, structural shapes, local handles, canonical cross-module identity, symbol visibility and public API validation.

Canonical details live in `docs/compiler-design-overview.md`.
